postcontent: I WANT TO MOVE THIS PISTOL OUT AND INTO THE HANDS OF SOMEONE WHO WILL APPRECIATE IT!I am selling my very rare and collectible FEMARU-FEGYVER-ES GEPGYAR R.T. 37M., otherwise known as a Hungarian Femaru Model 37M.  I origianlly put this out locally and have decided to put it out nationally.I paid $275 for this pistol at an estate/garage sale plus $100 for an original magazine as the pistol only came with an aftermarket mag. (Which I would include).  The seller and myself knew nothing about this pistol and after doing extensive research, I found out it's true value.  If you were to look at Gunbroker.com, Gunsamerica.com or Blue Book Values, you would see these go for anywhere between $375-$600+ depending on condition.  The original mags alone cost $150-$200 now.  This pistol is now a fully authenticated 1941 Femaru Model 37M with the addition of the original mag.I am a shooter, not a collector and I shoot regularly at the range.  After finding out the value of this pistol, I do not take this to the range anymore.  Naturally, it has been test fired and broken down and cleaned extensively.  I have a host of pistols and I do not need this lying around.  I put the condition of this pistol on the high side of 'good'.  I am mainly looking to get back out of this what I have put into it.The pistol was designed by Frommer, a prominent Hungarian gun manufacturer who produced quality weapons for the Hungarian Army.  It is styled after the proven design of the Colt 1911 as most manufacturers did and still do.  This pistol was made in Budapest, Hungary in 1941 and used by the Hungarian Army until Nazi Germany occupied Hungary and renamed it 'Pistole 37(u)', the lower case 'u' used to signify their Hungarian origins.As you can see from the photo's showing the serial # and the dates of manufacture, this pistol is over 75 years old.  The caliber was referred to as 9mm Kurz(European), which converts to .380acp.The barrel is interchangeable with the 7.65mm (.32acp) as is the mag.  The 7.65 was produced by Femaru for the German Luftwaffe and an additional safety was installed at the rear of the slide.  The only safety on this original Femaru 37M is a grip safety.I could go on and on about the history of the manufacturer, etc., but my space is limited.  I also have many more photo's, but I'm only allowed 3 here.If you need further info, more photo's or more intense documentation, you can contact me through 'contact seller' at the top of the page or text me at REDACTED.  I am located in Spring Hill, FL. As a note, this pistol is remarkably accurate given it's fixed sights.I am asking $425 and will entertain a reasonable offer.  Cashiers check only, no CC.  I do not want trades.  Receipt will be given.  You would be responsible for the cost of shipping, FFL fees to your FFL, etc.
